To create a file upload component with drag-and-drop functionality, I'll implement the following features:

1. **Dashed Border Drop Zone**: A visual area where users can drag and drop files.
2. **Upload Icon**: An icon to indicate the upload functionality.
3. **Instructional Text**: Text to guide users on how to use the component.
4. **Browse Files Link**: A link that allows users to open a file dialog to select files.
5. **List of Uploaded Files**: A display area for currently uploaded files, including progress bars and remove buttons.

I'll create a new component for this functionality. Let's proceed with the implementation. 

### File Upload Component Code

I'll create a new file named `FileUpload.tsx` in the `components/ui` directory. Here's the code for the component:

```tsx
// /vercel/share/v0-project/components/ui/FileUpload.tsx

import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { AiOutlineUpload } from 'react-icons/ai';

const FileUpload = () => {
  const [files, setFiles] = useState<File[]>([]);
  const [uploadProgress, setUploadProgress] = useState<{ [key: string]: number }>({});

  const handleDrop = (event: React.DragEvent<HTMLDivElement>) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    const droppedFiles = Array.from(event.dataTransfer.files);
    setFiles((prevFiles) => [...prevFiles, ...droppedFiles]);
    // Simulate upload progress
    droppedFiles.forEach((file) => {
      const progress = Math.random() * 100;
      setUploadProgress((prev) => ({ ...prev, [file.name]: progress }));
    });
  };

  const handleBrowseFiles = (event: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    const selectedFiles = Array.from(event.target.files || []);
    setFiles((prevFiles) => [...prevFiles, ...selectedFiles]);
    // Simulate upload progress
    selectedFiles.forEach((file) => {
      const progress = Math.random() * 100;
      setUploadProgress((prev) => ({ ...prev, [file.name]: progress }));
    });
  };

  const handleRemoveFile = (fileName: string) => {
    setFiles((prevFiles) => prevFiles.filter((file) => file.name !== fileName));
    setUploadProgress((prev) => {
      const newProgress = { ...prev };
      delete newProgress[fileName];
      return newProgress;
    });
  };

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col items-center">
      <div
        className="border-dashed border-2 border-gray-400 p-4 w-full text-center cursor-pointer"
        onDrop={handleDrop}
        onDragOver={(e) => e.preventDefault()}
      >
        <AiOutlineUpload className="text-4xl mb-2" />
        <p>Drag and drop files here or</p>
        <input
          type="file"
          multiple
          onChange={handleBrowseFiles}
          className="hidden"
          id="file-upload"
        />
        <label htmlFor="file-upload" className="text-blue-500 cursor-pointer">
          browse files
        </label>
      </div>
      <div className="mt-4 w-full">
        {files.map((file) => (
          <div key={file.name} className="flex items-center justify-between mt-2">
            <span>{file.name}</span>
            <div className="flex items-center">
              <div className="relative w-32">
                <div className="bg-gray-200 h-2 rounded">
                  <div
                    className="bg-blue-500 h-2 rounded"
                    style={{ width: `${uploadProgress[file.name] || 0}%` }}
                  />
                </div>
              </div>
              <button
                onClick={() => handleRemoveFile(file.name)}
                className="ml-2 text-red-500"
              >
                Remove
              </button>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default FileUpload;
```

### Summary

This `FileUpload` component includes a drag-and-drop area, an upload icon, instructional text, a 'browse files' link, and a list of uploaded files with progress bars and remove buttons. You can now integrate this component into your application wherever you need file upload functionality. 

